defs.name: functional
defs.docs: Functional programming with generic sequences

defs.name: MappedGenericSequence
defs.docs:
Defines the relationship between one generic sequence and another,
 for operations such as `map` and `zip`.

defs.name: Mapped
defs.docs: Mapped sequence type

defs.name: MappedSequence
defs.docs: Accessor type for a mapped generic sequence

defs.name: FunctionalSequence
defs.docs: Defines functional programming methods for generic sequences

defs.name: map
defs.value: fn <U, F> (self, f: F) -> MappedSequence<Self, T, U>
defs.docs: Maps a `GenericSequence` to another `GenericSequence`.

defs.name: zip
defs.value: fn <B, Rhs, U, F> (self, rhs: Rhs, f: F) -> MappedSequence<Self, T, U>
defs.docs:
Combines two `GenericSequence` instances and iterates through both of them,
 initializing a new `GenericSequence` with the result of the zipped mapping function.

defs.name: fold
defs.value: fn <U, F> (self, init: U, f: F) -> U
defs.docs: Folds (or reduces) a sequence of data into a single value.

defs.name: iter
defs.docs: `GenericArray` iterator implementation.

defs.name: GenericArrayIter
defs.docs: An iterator that moves out of a `GenericArray`

defs.name: as_slice
defs.docs: Returns the remaining items of this iterator as a slice

defs.name: as_mut_slice
defs.docs: Returns the remaining items of this iterator as a mutable slice

defs.name: sequence
defs.docs: Useful traits for manipulating sequences of data stored in `GenericArray`s

defs.name: GenericSequence
defs.docs: Defines some sequence with an associated length and iteration capabilities.

defs.name: Length
defs.docs: `GenericArray` associated length

defs.docs: Concrete sequence type used in conjuction with reference implementations of `GenericSequence`

defs.name: generate
defs.docs: Initializes a new sequence instance using the given function.

defs.value: fn <B, U, F> (self, lhs: GenericArray<B, Self::Length>, mut f: F) -> MappedSequence<GenericArray<B, Self::Length>, B, U>

defs.value: fn <B, Lhs, U, F> (self, lhs: Lhs, mut f: F) -> MappedSequence<Lhs, B, U>

defs.name: SequenceItem
defs.docs: Accessor for `GenericSequence` item type, which is really `IntoIterator::Item`

defs.name: Lengthen
defs.docs:
Defines any `GenericSequence` which can be lengthened or extended by appending
 or prepending an element to it.

defs.name: Longer
defs.docs: `GenericSequence` that has one more element than `Self`

defs.name: append
defs.docs: Returns a new array with the given element appended to the end of it.

defs.name: prepend
defs.docs: Returns a new array with the given element prepended to the front of it.

defs.name: Shorten
defs.docs: Defines a `GenericSequence` which can be shortened by removing the first or last element from it.

defs.name: Shorter
defs.docs: `GenericSequence` that has one less element than `Self`

defs.name: pop_back
defs.docs: Returns a new array without the last element, and the last element.

defs.name: pop_front
defs.docs:
Returns a new array without the first element, and the first element.

defs.name: Split
defs.docs: Defines a `GenericSequence` that can be split into two parts at a given pivot index.

defs.name: First
defs.docs: First part of the resulting split array

defs.name: Second
defs.docs: Second part of the resulting split array

defs.name: split
defs.docs: Splits an array at the given index, returning the separate parts of the array.

defs.name: Concat
defs.docs: Defines `GenericSequence`s which can be joined together, forming a larger array.

defs.name: Rest
defs.docs: Sequence to be concatenated with `self`

defs.name: Output
defs.docs: Resulting sequence formed by the concatenation.

defs.name: concat
defs.docs: Concatenate, or join, two sequences.

defs.name: ArrayLength
defs.docs: Trait making `GenericArray` work, marking types to be used as length of an array

defs.docs: Internal type used to generate a struct of appropriate size

defs.docs: Struct representing a generic array - `GenericArray<T, N>` works like [T; N]

defs.name: ArrayBuilder
defs.docs:
Creates an array one element at a time using a mutable iterator
 you can write to with `ptr::write`.

defs.name: iter_position
defs.docs: Creates a mutable iterator for writing to the array using `ptr::write`.

defs.name: into_inner
defs.docs:
When done writing (assuming all elements have been written to),
 get the inner array.

defs.name: ArrayConsumer
defs.docs: Consumes an array.

defs.name: iter_position
defs.docs:
Creates an iterator and mutable reference to the internal position
 to keep track of consumed elements.

defs.name: as_slice
defs.docs: Extracts a slice containing the entire array.

defs.name: as_mut_slice
defs.docs: Extracts a mutable slice containing the entire array.

defs.name: from_slice
defs.docs: Converts slice to a generic array reference with inferred length;

defs.name: from_mut_slice
defs.docs: Converts mutable slice to a mutable generic array reference

defs.name: clone_from_slice
defs.docs: Construct a `GenericArray` from a slice by cloning its content

defs.name: from_exact_iter
defs.docs: Creates a new `GenericArray` instance from an iterator with a known exact size.

defs.name: transmute
defs.docs:
A reimplementation of the `transmute` function, avoiding problems
 when the compiler can't prove equal sizes.
